The paper deals with complexity theory, specifically the relationship between hard-on-average languages in NP and the existence of one-way functions and hard problems in TFNP. This suggests that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) are likely categories. The paper also introduces a round-collapse theorem for computationally-sound protocols, which relates to information theory and communication complexity, indicating that cs.IT (Information Theory) may also be a relevant category. Additionally, the paper uses techniques from interactive complexity and argument systems, which could fall under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
